{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14936"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14936"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.16,0.26,0.19,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66426"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7624"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51877"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18641"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66426"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EImmunoglobulin A (IgA) is the predominant antibody class present at mucosal surfaces, providing an important barrier against pathogenic microorganisms. Some bacteria have evolved mechanisms to overcome this defence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria produces IgA proteases that contribute to mucosal invasion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staphylococcus aureus","Escherichia coli","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Treponema pallidum","Neisseria meningitidis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/strong\u003E produces IgA proteases that specifically cleave IgA1, the predominant immunoglobulin at mucosal surfaces. This enables the bacteria to evade mucosal immunity and facilitates invasion across the nasopharyngeal epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E produces various virulence factors including protein A, coagulase, and various toxins, but does not produce IgA proteases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E has multiple virulence factors including adhesins, toxins, and iron acquisition systems, but does not produce IgA proteases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E produces various virulence factors including capsule and pneumolysin but does not produce significant IgA proteases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/strong\u003E is the causative agent of syphilis and does not produce IgA proteases. Its pathogenicity involves other mechanisms of immune evasion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIgA proteases are important virulence factors that allow \u003Cem\u003EN. meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E to overcome mucosal immunity by degrading protective IgA antibodies, facilitating colonisation and invasion of the host.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["IgA proteases are virulence factors produced by several bacterial pathogens that colonise mucosal surfaces.","Neisseria meningitidis produces IgA proteases which help it evade mucosal immunity by cleaving IgA antibodies.","The ability to produce IgA proteases contributes to bacterial colonisation and invasion across mucosal barriers."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Mistry D, Stockley RA. IgA1 protease. Int J Biochem Cell Biol. 2006;38(8):1244-8. doi: 10.1016/j.biocel.2005.10.005. Epub 2005 Nov 2. PMID: 16293440; PMCID: PMC7108436.","Vidarsson G, Overbeeke N, Stemerding AM, van den Dobbelsteen G, van Ulsen P, van der Ley P, Kilian M, van de Winkel JG. Working mechanism of immunoglobulin A1 (IgA1) protease: cleavage of IgA1 antibody to Neisseria meningitidis PorA requires de novo synthesis of IgA1 Protease. Infect Immun. 2005 Oct;73(10):6721-6. doi: 10.1128/IAI.73.10.6721-6726.2005. PMID: 16177349; PMCID: PMC1230903.","Spoerry C, Karlsson J, Aschtgen MS, Loh E. Neisseria meningitidis IgA1-specific serine protease exhibits novel cleavage activity against IgG3. Virulence. 2021 Dec;12(1):389-403. doi: 10.1080/21505594.2021.1871822. PMID: 33459578; PMCID: PMC7834093."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51877"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14936"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51877"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T08:55:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T08:56:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7624"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66426"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a ju